To store the relevant data for later binding and drawing, you can create a `Model` class with a vector of `Mesh` objects as a member variable, and add a `Bind()` and `Draw()` method to the `Renderer3D` class.

In the `Model` class, you can store the data for each mesh in the `Mesh` class, which should contain the vertex data in the form of a vertex buffer object (VBO) and an index buffer object (IBO), as well as the texture data.

In the `Bind()` method of the `Renderer3D` class, you can bind the VBO and IBO for each mesh and set the appropriate vertex attributes. In the `Draw()` method, you can draw the mesh using `glDrawElements()` and specify the number of indices to draw using the size of the IBO for that mesh.

Here is some pseudocode for what the `Bind()` and `Draw()` methods in the `Renderer3D` class might look like:
```
void Renderer3D::Bind(Model& model)
{
    for (const auto& mesh : model.meshes)
    {
        // Bind the VBO and IBO for this mesh
        glBindBuffer(GL_ARRAY_BUFFER, mesh.vbo);
        glBindBuffer(GL_ELEMENT_ARRAY_BUFFER, mesh.ibo);

        // Set the vertex attributes for this mesh
        // Assuming the vertex data is laid out as follows:
        //  3 floats for position, 3 floats for normal, 2 floats for texture coords
        glVertexAttribPointer(0, 3, GL_FLOAT, GL_FALSE, 8 * sizeof(float), (void*)0);
        glEnableVertexAttribArray(0);
        glVertexAttribPointer(1, 3, GL_FLOAT, GL_FALSE, 8 * sizeof(float), (void*)(3 * sizeof(float)));
        glEnableVertexAttribArray(1);
        glVertexAttribPointer(2, 2, GL_FLOAT, GL_FALSE, 8 * sizeof(float), (void*)(6 * sizeof(float)));
        glEnableVertexAttribArray(2);
    }
}

void Renderer3D::Draw(Model& model)
{
    for (const auto& mesh : model.meshes)
    {
        // Bind the texture for this mesh
        mesh.texture->Bind();

        // Draw the mesh using the number of indices in the IBO
        glDrawElements(GL_TRIANGLES, mesh.iboSize, GL_UNSIGNED_INT, 0);
    }
}
```
Keep in mind that this is just one way to store and draw a 3D model using OpenGL. There are many other approaches you can take depending on your specific requirements and design choices.

Sure! Here is a simple class that wraps an OpenGL texture using the Resource Acquisition Is Initialization (RAII) principle:
```
#include <GL/gl.h>

class Texture
{
public:
    Texture()
    {
        glGenTextures(1, &m_textureId);
    }

    ~Texture()
    {
        glDeleteTextures(1, &m_textureId);
    }

    Texture(const Texture& other) = delete;
    Texture& operator=(const Texture& other) = delete;

    Texture(Texture&& other) noexcept
    {
        std::swap(m_textureId, other.m_textureId);
    }

    Texture& operator=(Texture&& other) noexcept
    {
        std::swap(m_textureId, other.m_textureId);
        return *this;
    }

    GLuint getId() const
    {
        return m_textureId;
    }

private:
    GLuint m_textureId;
};
```
This class generates an OpenGL texture when an instance of `Texture` is created, and deletes the texture when the instance is destroyed. The copy constructor and copy assignment operator are deleted to prevent copying of `Texture` objects, and the move constructor and move assignment operator are implemented to allow moving of `Texture` objects.

You can use the `Texture` class like this:
```
void foo()
{
    // Generate an OpenGL texture
    Texture texture;
    GLuint textureId = texture.getId();

    // Use the texture
    glBindTexture(GL_TEXTURE_2D, textureId);
    // ...
}
```
When `foo` returns, the `Texture` object will be destroyed and the OpenGL texture will be deleted.

