In JUnit, you can set an environment variable for a single test method by using the `@Test` annotation with the `@Before` and `@After` annotations. Here's an example:
```java
import org.junit.After;
import org.junit.Before;
import org.junit.Test;

public class MyTest {

    private String originalValue;

    @Before
    public void setUp() {
        // Save the original value of the environment variable
        originalValue = System.getenv("MY_VAR");
        // Set the value of the environment variable for this test
        System.setEnv("MY_VAR", "test-value");
    }

    @After
    public void tearDown() {
        // Restore the original value of the environment variable
        System.setEnv("MY_VAR", originalValue);
    }

    @Test
    public void myTest() {
        // Your test code here
    }
}
```
In this example, the `setUp()` method is annotated with `@Before`, which means that it will be executed before each test method. In `setUp()`, the original value of the environment variable is saved, and then the value of the environment variable is set to `"test-value"`.

Similarly, the `tearDown()` method is annotated with `@After`, which means that it will be executed after each test method. In `tearDown()`, the original value of the environment variable is restored.

By using this approach, the environment variable will be set only for the `myTest()` method and will not affect other tests in the same class.

