mutation readCSVFile($file: Upload!) {
  readCSV(file: $file) {
    rows {
      cells
    }
  }
}
```
The `readCSV` function would be implemented in your GraphQL resolvers and would use the `fastify` `fileUploader` plugin to process the uploaded file. Here is an example of how the `readCSV` resolver function might be implemented:
```
const readCSV = (obj, args, context, info) => {
  return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    const { file } = args;

    context.fileUploader.process(file, (err, data) => {
      if (err) {
        return reject(err);
      }

      const rows = data.rows.map(row => ({ cells: row.cells }));
      return resolve({ rows });
    });
  });
};
```
This function takes the uploaded file and uses the `fileUploader` to process it, returning the rows of the CSV file in the expected format for the GraphQL response.

